                  </hi>. I am the sister-in-law of Ruth Adams, now Ruth Buck—I married her brother—I was present at the marriage of Ruth Adams to Thomas Stepheu Buck, in 1853, at the parish church at Wooton Bassett—she</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186806080043"></xptr>
               <p>still resides in the neighbourhood—I do not know how long they lived together—they left the place after they were married.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">The certificate of the marriage was read</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18680608-name-239" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18680608-name-239" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18680608-name-239" type="surname" value="ADAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18680608-name-239" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS ADAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the husband of the last witness, and brother of the prisoner's first wife—I saw her three weeks yesterday—I was not at the marriage, but I saw them living together afterwards—they did so for six or. seven yean, and had two children—they lived at Bath some time—Wooton Bassett is twenty-five miles from Bath—Buck left his wife, and she eame home.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did the prisoner ever mention that his wife had committed adultery with a man named Fox? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I never heard it.</p>
